<p>'night, MotherWritten by<ref target="/wiki/Marsha_Norman" title="Marsha Norman">Marsha Norman</ref>CharactersJessie CatesThelma CatesDate premiered1982Place premiered<ref target="/wiki/American_Repertory_Theater" title="American Repertory Theater">American Repertory Theater</ref><ref target="/wiki/Cambridge,_Massachusetts" title="Cambridge, Massachusetts">Cambridge, Massachusetts</ref>Original languageEnglishGenreDrama</p>
<p>'night, Mother is a play by <ref target="/wiki/Americans" title="Americans">American</ref> playwright <ref target="/wiki/Marsha_Norman" title="Marsha Norman">Marsha Norman</ref>. The play won the 1983 <ref target="/wiki/Pulitzer_Prize_for_Drama" title="Pulitzer Prize for Drama">Pulitzer Prize for Drama</ref> and was nominated for the <ref target="/wiki/Tony_Award_for_Best_Play" title="Tony Award for Best Play">Tony Award for Best Play</ref>.<ref target="#cite_note-1">[1]</ref></p>
<p>The play is about a daughter, Jessie, and her mother, Thelma. It begins with Jessie calmly telling her Mama that by morning she will be dead, as she plans to commit suicide that very evening. The subsequent dialogue between Jessie and Mama slowly reveals her reasons for her decision, her life with Mama, and how thoroughly she has planned her own death, culminating in a disturbing, yet unavoidable, climax.<ref target="#cite_note-2">[2]</ref></p>

